26
November
UBA Ghana Launches Partnership With GESRO Co-operative Credit Union

UBA Ghana yesterday successfully launched a partnership with GESRO Co-operative Credit Union at the Akromah Plaza,Takoradi. This pact is set to bring to the doorstep of GESRO members nationwide UBA's unparralel banking services and solutions. Services such as bundled E-products,Africash amongst others can now be accessed by GESRO Members nationwide.

The member of Parliament for Takoradi Hon,Okyere Darko praised both UBA and GESRO for this innovative partnership. He further called on the other credit unions in the country to follow suit.

In his presentation, the Regional Director Mr Charles Odonkor who deputized for the MD/CEO ,Mr Gabriel Edgal,said UBA is the Bank of Choice as we are always the first to bring innovative products and services to our customers and the industry at large, eg Cashless account,Wise Alertand now this Partnership which is the first in the country and the industry.

He expressed his profound gratitude to the GESRO team for seeing to the logical conclusion , what started as a dream and an idea.

Mr Kusi Boakye Yiadom, CEO of GESRO espoused his appreciation to the management of UBA Ghana for the support rendered in making this dream come alive.He further opined that, the partnership he believes will go a very long way to make his members nationwide enjoy UBA's services in the comfort of their locations.

18
November
UBA Ghana Unveils CEO's Breakfast Forum

 UBA Ghana yesterday unveiled another Novelty dubbed CEO's Business Breakfast Forum. The maiden forum in Ghana had in attendance the Minister for Trade and Industry Hon. Hanna Tetteh, High Commissioner of Nigeria, CEOs' of corporate Ghana and the Media.

The Executive Director Mr Daniel Addo in his presentation, proposed that West Africa Governments and regulators should allow West African local currencies to be convertible with one another for ease of trade and also to reduce pressure on the countries foreign reserves.

MD/CEO Mr Gabriel Edgal urged governments in the sub-region to work together to streamline tariff imposition, enhance transportation and infrastructure to make trading comfortable in the sub-region. in addition several fora have been organized to promote regional integration saying leaders in West Africa would have to take immediate action to stimulate trade in the region.

Hanna Tetteh, Minister for Trade and Industry who was the keynote speaker mentioned that ECOWAS, as an organization, has not succeeded in promoting regional trade. She further tasked ECOWAS do more to boost trade and grow economies of the member countries.

October
UBA (Ghana) Unveils Africash &Afritrade Products
From L-R
Daniel Addo, Executive Director ,UBA Ghana, Stella Okojie, Gabriel Edgal,MD/CEO,Emeka Udegbulem, Group Head, Marketing & Corporate Relations, UBA Africa
United Bank for Africa Ghana (UBA Ghana), last week unveiled two new products - Africash and Afritrade onto the Ghanaian market. Launching the two new products, MD/CEO Mr Gabriel Edgal said there could be no economic integration without free flow of trade within the region, hence the bank's effort towards integrating and progressing trade across Africa.

31
August
UBA MD/CEO Calls On Ghana's Minister For Trade & Industry

Mr Gabriel Edgal MD/CEO of UBA Ghana recently paid a courtesy call on the Minister for Trade and Industry, Honourable Hanna Tetteh at her office in Accra.

The meeting focused mainly on trade related issues in Ghana and the West African Sub-region. Mr. Edgal used the opportunity to espouse UBA's Pan-African agenda which has so far culminated in presence in 19 African countries.

The MD/CEO also used the platform to introduce to the Minister and officials from the ministry, the banks Africa Trade platform and pledged UBA's preparedness to partner the ministry so as to foster a mutually beneficial relationship.

The Honourable Minister praised UBA for its support for trade in the sub-region and expressed her desire for further collaboration between her Ministry and UBA for the promotion of trade in Ghana and West Africa as a whole.

14
July
UBA Ghana Trains Staff

UBA Ghana is organizing a massive internal training aimed at building the Capacity of Staff to deliver on the operational mandate of the Bank. The objective of the training is to provide staff the opportunity to learn the current trends and developments in Banking, particularly Domestic Operations (DOMOPS), Treasury Operations (TROPS), Foreign Operations (FOPS), Clearing, and Relationship Management amongst others.

The 10 Stream training is divided into Core Basic Banking and Core Intermediate Banking with a class size of 45 participants drawn from the following departments:


1.    Banking Operations
2.    Treasury
3.    IT
4.    E-Business
5.    Marketing
6.    Corporate Banking
7.    Retail Banking
8.    Customer Service
9.    9. Service Quality


Mr. Richard Oppong Head of training opined "we hope to have adequately trained 450 staff of the Bank at the end of the three month long training" at the opening ceremony.

Closing the opening ceremony Mr Gabriel Edgal MD/CEO advised the participants to crave for further knowledge in administering their desk effectively as UBA continually invests in the education of its staff.

June
UBA Rewards Loyal Customers
UBA rewarded loyal customers through the second Savings Promo dubbed “UBA World Cup Double Triple Savings Promo”. The promo which is ongoing and due to close first week in July rewarded 15 participants in the promo.

26 years old Christopher Boateng Tema based business man won the ultimate prize of an all expense paid trip for two to watch Ghana’s Black Stars in South Africa.

A 32 inch Samsung Flat-screen set went to Sahura Sannie,the second prize winner while Mr. Anaele Okoro took home a double door refrigerator for placing third.

Customers and non - customers of the bank were required to open or top up their savings account with a minimum deposit of GH¢100.00 for two to three months without withdrawals to earn double or tripple interest on the deposit at the end of the promotion.

01
June
UBA Staff Show Love On International Children's Day
 
Staff of United Bank for Africa (Ghana) as part of the International Children’s Day Celebration which fell on Thursday May 27 made donations to a number of orphanages across the bank’s areas of operation.

In addition to spending time with the staff and children of the homes,the Staff of UBA presented assorted food items, clothing, stationary and cash donations totaling over GH¢ 7,000.00 Seven Thousand Ghana Cedis.

The five Orphanages visited namely, Country Side Orphanage, Bawjiase, Kids Care International, Tema, Fathers’ Home Care Sekondi, Kumasi Children’s Home, Good Shepherd Happy Home in Aflao each received cash donations, used clothing, bags of rice, fruit juices, cooking oil, loaves of bread, stationary amongst others.

Making the presentation at the Country Side Orphanage, the Head of Corporate Communications, Mr Eli Muzzu mentioned that the gesture by the Staff of the bank is a demonstration of one of the core values of the bank which is empathy.

“We recognize that on a day like this, there is no better way to bring smiles to the faces of these unfortunate children than to spend time with them and donate our widow’s mite.” UBA’s core values are Humility, Empathy, Integrity and Resilience (HEIR).

Receiving the items on behalf of the children, Captain Rtd & Mrs. Joe Yeboah, the parents of the house applauded the Staff of UBA and prayed for Gods blessing for the institution and its staff. Mrs. Boafo Yeboah lamented that their location has made it difficult to attract regular support of this kind. She used the opportunity to appeal to other corporate institutions to emulate the laudable example of the Staff of UBA and support them with the upkeep of the 160 children presently in their care.
18
February
UBA Africash To Deepen Integration

The Managing Director and Chief Executive Officer of United Bank for Africa (Ghana) Ltd., Mr Gabriel Edgal has described the bank’s Africash instant money transfer product as a step towards financial integration of the African continent.

Mr Edgal, who was addressing media men at the banks 2010 maiden health walk and bonding exercise dubbed “Jogging to Bond” at the Ghana International School stated emphatically that  “Before the continent could succeed in the integration of cultures, goods and services, there was the need for strong financial integration among countries in Africa”.

The introduction of an instant money transfer product by UBA called “Africash” is a bold step towards financial integration. Furthermore unlike the other money transfer systems which put Ghana and other African countries on the receiving end, UBA Africash makes it possible for one to both send and receive money within Africa. An added advantage is the fact that “Africash” is instant and extremely convenient for both sender and receiver he added.


In conclusion, Mr Edgal stated that the bank had presence in 19 countries in Africa, and footprint in Europe, Asia and America to fulfill its desire in delivering financial services to businesses round the world that want to deal with Africa and Africans who want to transact business with the world.
